## Section 8 — Thumbnail / cover workflow

TikTok uses your video's first frame as the default cover but lets you choose any frame or upload a custom image. A custom thumbnail increases click-through on profile views and search.

### Quick thumbnail workflow (10 minutes per video)

**Option A: Best frame from video (fastest)**
```python
def extract_thumbnail(video_path: str, output_path: str, timestamp: str = "00:00:02"):
    """Extract frame at timestamp as thumbnail — use a visually strong moment"""
    subprocess.run([
        "ffmpeg", "-y", "-ss", timestamp,
        "-i", video_path,
        "-vframes", "1",
        "-q:v", "2",
        output_path
    ], check=True)
```
Choose a timestamp where the most visually striking frame appears.

**Option B: Canva (5 minutes, free)**
1. Open Canva → New design → TikTok Video Cover (1080×1920)
2. Upload your best scene image as background
3. Add the hook line as large text (white, bold, slight dark overlay behind it)
4. Export as PNG
5. Upload as custom cover when posting on TikTok

**Thumbnail best practices for your niche:**
- Show the most visually dramatic scene image as background
- Overlay the hook line in 2–3 large words max
- Dark, cinematic color grade
- No human faces needed — the visual itself is the draw
- Avoid cluttered text — one strong visual + one short phrase wins

