## Section 12 — Common mistakes to avoid

### Mistakes that kill channels before they start

**1. Posting inconsistently**
Three videos one week, nothing for two weeks destroys algorithmic momentum. One video every single day beats burst posting. Set a schedule and protect it.

**2. Copying hooks without understanding why they work**
A hook works because it creates a specific emotion in a specific audience. Copying the words without the emotion logic produces flat content. Understand *why* the hook stops the scroll.

**3. Ignoring completion rate**
Views are a vanity metric. Completion rate is what the TikTok algorithm actually rewards. A 10K-view video with 80% completion gets pushed harder than a 100K-view video with 15% completion. Check analytics every 48 hours.

**4. Making videos too long**
45–55 seconds is the sweet spot for this format. Anything over 60 seconds loses significant completion rate with a teen+ audience. Resist the urge to add more story.

**5. Inconsistent visual style**
If Scene 1 looks like a dark oil painting and Scene 4 looks like a bright cartoon, the video feels cheap. Always prefix every image prompt with your `visual_style` phrase.

**6. Uploading during bad hours**
Posting at 3 AM means your video competes for algorithm slots when engagement is lowest. Your first 30 minutes of views matter most. Post when your audience is active.

**7. Adding copyrighted music**
TikTok auto-detects copyrighted audio and either mutes the video or kills its distribution. Only use royalty-free tracks from Pixabay, FreePD, or YouTube Audio Library.

**8. Changing niche before giving it time**
Niche-switching before 30 videos is almost always a mistake. The algorithm needs a consistent content signal to know who to show your videos to. Commit to one niche for 60 days minimum.

**9. Over-engineering before proving the concept**
Don't spend two weeks perfecting your automation pipeline before posting your first video. Post manually, get real feedback, then automate the parts that are working.

**10. Not keeping a content log**
Write down the hook, format, emotional tone, and performance stats for every video. This is your data. After 20 videos, patterns emerge that no blog post can predict for your specific account.

